[1]
Date: Wed 7 Sep 2011
Source: Adelaide Now [edited]
http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/virus-fears-for-south-australian-poultry/story-e6frea6u-1226130930844


South Australian (SA) poultry farmers fear a new poultry virus,
similar to strains found in China, may have a devastating impact on
their flocks.

The avian paramyxovirus has spread to Australia for the 1st time,
destroying entire pigeon flocks and worrying poultry farmers about the
implications for their birds.

Authorities have already urged pigeon fanciers to ground their pigeons
to help prevent the spread of the virus.

Biosecurity SA (South Australia) chief veterinary officer Rob Rahaley
yesterday [6 Sep 2-11] inspected about 500 pigeons -- all from South
Australia -- at the Royal Adelaide Show and passed them fit.

Dr Rahaley said the avian paramyxovirus is similar to the devastating
Newcastle disease in poultry and is previously unreported in
Australia.

It has killed 80-90 per cent of pigeons in 6 flocks of both racing and
show pigeons in the Shepparton district in northwestern Victoria and
Melbourne. The virus has led to a warning to SA pigeon owners to keep
their birds at home and restrict any movement of them in or out of the
state.

Dr Rahaley said while there had been no reports of the virus in South
Australian birds, the death of pigeons in northwestern Melbourne and
Shepparton posed the potential for the virus to be transmitted here.

"We're strongly advising pigeon fanciers to stop any movement of their
birds in connection with their hobby until further notice," Dr Rahaley
said.

"As virulent paramyxoviruses isolated from pigeons are capable of
infecting poultry, we're also advising producers to prevent any
contact between poultry, turkeys, emus, and ostriches, with wild birds
or pigeons, both indirectly and directly, for example via feed and
water.

Biosecurity SA will be monitoring the situation in Victoria and will
investigate any reports we receive in South Australia of birds
becoming ill."

Dr Rahaley said most commercial poultry flocks were vaccinated against
Newcastle disease and it would probably provide some safeguard.

"The major implication is to try and limit its spread within the
pigeon population and make sure that it doesn't cross into commercial
poultry," he said.

Bird owners who notice any unusual signs should contact the Animal
Disease Watch hotline on 1800 675 888.

