[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Australia can be seen at
http://healthmap.org/r/01qe. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

[Pigeon paramyxovirus type 1 (PPMV-1) is closely related to Newcastle
disease virus (NDV), as they are both classified in the same family of
viruses, _Paramyxoviridae_, and are within the same serotype, referred
to as paramyxovirus type 1. In spite of their close relationship,
there are clear antigenic (antibody stimulating) differences between
NDV and PPMV-1, which can only be determined by laboratory testing.

PPMV-1 was isolated for the 1st time from pigeons in the Middle East
in late 1970s and subsequently was introduced throughout North Africa.
The virus was reported in Italy in 1981 and from 1981 to 1984, spread
throughout the world. PPMV-1 has been isolated from pigeons, doves,
and ornamental birds in addition to commercial and feral pigeons. It
has been suggested that PPMV-1 is a variant form of NDV of chickens
and possibly emerged as a result of frequent transmission of the virus
from chickens to pigeons.

In 1984, a number of outbreaks in commercial poultry flocks in the UK,
with clinical signs such as drop in egg production, nervous signs, and
increased mortality were attributed to infection with PPMV-1.
Contamination of feed with pigeon feces and carcasses was considered
the main source of most of these outbreaks. However, in 2001, it was
speculated that a case of egg production drop in a commercial layer
flock in US was attributed to the contamination of the feed
ingredients with infected pigeon carcasses (PPMV-1 was isolated from
the pigeon carcasses but not from the layer flock), although this was
never proven.

Because of historical evidence that demonstrates the ability of some
pigeon-origin isolates of PPMV-1 to cause clinical disease in
commercial poultry flocks in other parts of the world (such as in
Europe, 1984), there is concern that these viruses might spread from
pigeons to commercial poultry flocks and cause clinical disease. There
have been a number of studies in the US that have assessed the
virulence of pigeon-origin PPMV-1 isolations in chickens under
experimental conditions.

To summarize, the PPMV-1 that has been increasingly isolated from
pigeon operations in Canada demands monitoring and appropriate
measures for 2 main reasons
- These viruses are able to cause disease and mortality in
non-vaccinated pigeons and result in losses to these operations, and
- If adequate biosecurity is not in place, there is a potential to
spread to commercial chicken and turkey flocks.

Even if the infection with the PPMV-1 isolates in commercial poultry
flocks is not causing overt clinical signs, it may provide an
opportunity for the virus to circulate in these flocks for an extended
period of time and based on available experimental studies,
potentially gain more ability to cause clinical signs and disease in
commercial poultry flocks in the future. The potential for this to
happen under field conditions is not known.

In order to minimize any potential risk of PPMV-1 in pigeon operations
and commercial poultry flocks, the following measures should be
considered:
- All suspect cases of disease in pigeons (especially those showing
nervous signs) should be monitored closely and proper diagnosis should
be sought in consultation with your veterinarian.
- Since pigeons can be infected with both PPMV-1 and exotic NDV,
isolates should be evaluated to make sure that they are not infected
with Exotic NDV. This can only be done at the laboratory.
- Since there is a possibility that non-vaccinated sick pigeons
infected with PPMV-1 may spread the infection to other pigeons and
possibly commercial poultry flocks, all commercial pigeon operations
should implement adequate vaccination programs against PPMV-1, to be
administered in consultation with your veterinarian. Correct age,
dose, and vaccine administration are important factors to induce
strong immunity in vaccinated birds and protect them against field
challenge.
- All pigeon operations should implement adequate biosecurity measures
as the PPMV-1, like NDV, is extremely contagious and can be spread to
other farms and lofts through infected birds, people, equipment,
clothing, and many other mechanical vectors.
- Owners of commercial poultry flocks should avoid any direct or
indirect contact with potentially infected pigeon operations and
practice adequate biosecurity measures. This is more important for
commercial flocks that are not commonly vaccinated against NDV.

The paramyxoviruses are an important cause of respiratory disease in
children. Illnesses include croup, bronchiolitis, and pneumonitis.

This group of viruses shares similar features; they possess a double
layered envelope with spikes, have a helical symmetry, and contain a
negative stranded RNA genome. An RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RDRP)
is contained within the virus particle. Paramyxoviruses replicate in
the cytoplasm and are released by budding. Virus-specific antigens
include those associated with the envelope and those contained within
the nucleocapsid.

The host range for the paramyxoviruses includes humans and monkeys.

These viruses produce multinucleated giant cells (syncytia) by
production of a cell fusing factor, and then cause host cell lysis.

One interesting note, Hendra virus is also in the _Paramyxoviridae_
grouping. I toss that trivial fact out because some one will decide it
came from the flying foxes. That cannot be true, but it is interesting
to note the number of _Paramyxoviridae_ manifestations in Australia
this year (2011).

Portions of this have been extracted from
http://www.cehs.siu.edu/fix/medmicro/param.htm and
http://www.thepoultrysite.com/articles/1366/pigeon-paramyxovirus-type-1-and-its-importance-for-the-commercial-poultry-industry.
- Mod.TG]
